\subsection{Gayatri Mantra}

\mna{\hspace{1.5em}In Sanscrit the syllables of the word \textbf{Mantra} (\saha{मंत्र}) are broken up as the root, \textbf{Man} (\saha{युव}): the root of \textbf{manas} (\saha{मनस्}) which means ``mind" or ``think", and \textbf{Tra} (\saha{त्रा}): \emph{vehicle} or \emph{instrument}. Tra is also translated as ``the heat of life." And of course we associate \textbf{Ra} with the sun.}

The Gayatri Mantra is reputed to be a very popular mantra. Gayatri was this milk maid, in  Hindu mythology who wasn't down with it when the goddess Indra came to fetch her to become Brahma's bride because Brahma was afraid his wife Saraswati wouldn't arrive on time for a \emph{very important} ceremony. Saraswati was pissed and reigned down punishments on all involved, except Gayatri, whom she eventually befriended and honored with the role of teaching humankind the art of Mantra. Below is the ``long" version. Interestingly I read somewhere that the ``short" version preceded the ``long" version, historically.

