\subsection*{Shangó Shangó}
\index{Shango}
Shangó is the Yoruba deity of lightening and thunder. Similarly to the Hindu Shiva and Norse Odin and Thor, Shangó is fierce as can be. A warrior. Sometimes we use this chant in yoga when we're doing Virabhadrasana (warrior) poses. Before he was a god, Shangó was a human being; a king. At some point he committed some horrible act of rage and destruction. As an act of repentance for what he had done, Shangó hung himself from a tree (sound familiar, fans of Odin?) and died. \emph{Ọba so} is Yoruba for \emph{the king hung}. Seeing this fearless act of selflessness and ultimate sacrifice, the creator, Olodumare resurrected Shangó as a deity. Thus the famous saying, "Ọba kò so": The king did not hang. 

We learned this chant from members of an Ile (Orisha temple) called Ileṣa Ire, who came to Pensacola from Atlanta, GA and Gainesville, FL at the behest of our friends NileriWosan and Baba Adelana Balewa. 

