\subsection{Ardhanārīśvara}

We wondered how the (god-damn) (so-called) yoga (so-called) community would accept or even \mna{\textbf{Cis} refers to people who people who identify as the gender they were told they were when they were born. \textbf{Adam Powers} is author of a hilarious article on polyamory titled, ``The Only Poly People You’ll Ever Date''.} receive Rivka's gender fluidity, or anyone else's including mine should I ever chose to come out. Mostly they're too busy selling multi-marketing natural remedies to notice it. We knew about the Hijras, who are in Pakistan and Bangladesh officially recognized as a third gender. So we did a little bit of research and came upon the androgynous deity Ardhanarishvara (Sanskrit: \saha{अर्धनारीश्वर}, Ardhanārīśvara), who is the incarnate union of Shiva and Parvati; The synthesis of soul and nature, masculine and feminine, Purusha and Prakriti. \par

We had been looking for a mantra for the cultivation of androgyny. It's a prefect chant for a time when we are, as a society, in recovery from what Adam Powers so eloquently referred to as the Cis Virus.
